TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Assignment of Workers to Jobs in an Economy with Coordination Frictions
AU  - Shimer, Robert
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/444551
DO  - 10.1086/444551
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 996
EP  - 1025
VL  - 113
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper studies the assignment of heterogeneous workers to heterogeneous jobs. Owing to the anonymity of a large labor market, workers use mixed strategies when applying for jobs. This randomness generates coordination frictions. Two workers may apply for a particular job, whereas an identical job gets no applications. The model generates assortative matching, with a positive but imperfect correlation between matched workers? and firms? types. It predicts that a worker?s wage is increasing in her job?s productivity and a firm?s profit is increasing in its employees? productivity. The model also yields a version of the welfare theorems.
AB  - This paper studies the assignment of heterogeneous workers to heterogeneous jobs. Owing to the anonymity of a large labor market, workers use mixed strategies when applying for jobs. This randomness generates coordination frictions. Two workers may apply for a particular job, whereas an identical job gets no applications. The model generates assortative matching, with a positive but imperfect correlation between matched workers? and firms? types. It predicts that a worker?s wage is increasing in her job?s productivity and a firm?s profit is increasing in its employees? productivity. The model also yields a version of the welfare theorems.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/444551
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/444551
Y2  - 2024/03/19
