TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is Bigger Better? Customer Base Expansion through Word‐of‐Mouth Reputation
AU  - Rob, Rafael
AU  - Fishman, Arthur
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/444552
DO  - 10.1086/444552
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1146
EP  - 1162
VL  - 113
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A model of gradual reputation formation through a process of continuous investment in product quality is developed. We assume that the ability to produce high?quality products requires continuous investment and that as a consequence of informational frictions, such as search costs, information about firms? past performance diffuses only gradually in the market. This leads to a dual process of growth of a firm?s customer base and an increase in the firm?s investment in quality. The model predicts, therefore, that the longer its tenure as a high?quality producer, the more a firm invests in quality. We relate this finding to empirical work on online commerce as well as on traditional industries.
AB  - A model of gradual reputation formation through a process of continuous investment in product quality is developed. We assume that the ability to produce high?quality products requires continuous investment and that as a consequence of informational frictions, such as search costs, information about firms? past performance diffuses only gradually in the market. This leads to a dual process of growth of a firm?s customer base and an increase in the firm?s investment in quality. The model predicts, therefore, that the longer its tenure as a high?quality producer, the more a firm invests in quality. We relate this finding to empirical work on online commerce as well as on traditional industries.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/444552
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/444552
Y2  - 2024/03/19
